social_posts.post_text: Many, many moons later I am finally editioning two images from the reindeer migration I had the honor of photographing with the help of the amazing @lepi70 in my native Sweden. The largest size will be 30” x 40” printed by @lightsource_sf (they nail the difficult whites of ice and snow). Final print edition details coming January. Happy Holidays ❄️🎄❄️

The short winter days with the slanted, champagne colored light on our tilted earth in its seasonal dance with the sun has me thinking about how our stories exist in time. The slippery, invisible stories that we tell each other as we hurtle through space. I’m playing around with folded photographs to explore this idea of mapping our intangible stories across spacetime.
 
We, along with the entire solar system, are moving towards Vega at a speed of 15 mi / 24.1 km per second. Vega will become the brightest star in the sky in about 210,000 years.
 
To the the astronomers, cosmonauts, scientists and physicists that follow this account: Apologies for my science salad posts. I admire your work and I wish I could speak the language of math better ✨💫☄️ #collage #spacetime #perihelion

Just after dawn broke on Lundi Gras (the day before Mardi Gras) in 2020. This Pope of Mardi Gras told me he had been up all night, blessed me (yeah, you rite) and hit me up for a few bucks. A new year is upon us, which means New Orleans is officially in Mardi Gras Season. For the rest of my days, I will miss this glorious city and state. #yeahyouright #NewOrleans #MardiGrasSeason

I have always been drawn to the physical and conceptual edges of America. At the bottom of Louisiana, there is shrinking patch of land —  Isle de Jean Charles — that once encompassed more than 22,000 acres, but today only 320 acres (or less) remain. For over 170 years, it has been the historical homeland and burial ground of the state-recognized tribe of the Isle de Jean Charles Band of Biloxi-Chitimacha-Choctaw people. The state is in the process of relocating them inland as their home slips into the Gulf of Mexico.

The road leading to Isle de Jean Charles has its own tide schedule. This new Timescape of that road is comprised of photos made 17 minutes apart, as the tide flowed in. At some point I will re-do this Timescape. I wonder how long it will be before the road is underwater all the time. 

American Timescapes is an in-progress project that addresses the ephemerality of the American experience across deep time. Each artwork is comprised of three separate photographs of a landscape/region made minutes, hours, days, or years apart. These prints are cut, folded and combined to create a 3-dimensional photo sculpture. Artwork size: 15" X 15" on a 17" x 17" sheet. Comes framed in a custom shadow box at 23.5" x 23.5" x 1.75.” Printed by my friends at @pushdotstudio  #americantimescapes #timescape #timescapes #deeptime #climatechange #risingseas #globalwarming #louisiana

Come spring, this feed will Mars, Mars, Mars! I am thrilled to be joining an absolutely amazing international team of scientists and engineers for a two week simulation of life on Mars (spacesuits and all) at the Mars Desert Research Station in Utah, courtesy of The Mars Society. In my own work, this year is all about the stories that we are telling about our future. In the meantime, if you are curious, check out our crew website (link in bio) 🚀🤖
Accidental possibilities ✂️

Last night at the Seattle Museum of Flight at Yuri's Night, an international celebration held every April 12 (or thereabout) to celebrate all things space. It is named for the first human to launch into space, Yuri Gagarin  who flew the Vostok 1 spaceship on April 12, 1961 🚀🤖✨

A Grand Canyon Timescape (with a trash can) for Earth Day. I am thinking about deep time a lot lately - deep time is a concept championed by geologists and astronomers, the ones among us who interpret long ago events recorded within our Earth’s geological features and far-away planets and stars. When gazing at the Grand Canyon, millions of years are visible to us, compressed into a single instant. Today we consider what we, as the fleeting custodians of this time and place, might owe our descendants. Our story is also their story. #AmericanTimescapes #EarthDay #GrandCanyon #InfiniteInstant #deeptime

In addition to serving as a journalist for @marstransatlantic261  I am also producing work for my projects Ex Astra, American Timescapes and Beneath a Paper Moon, all which consider storytelling across time (past, present and future). Storytelling has long served as an essential catalyst in the alchemy of scientific discovery. It is the vessel that carries within it the fragile essence of our humanity, infusing the sterile precision of data with the warm pulse of our imperfect hearts. Every simulation carried out at the Mars Desert Research Station is a story, an important draft in the larger unfolding story of humans to Mars. One day, a human being will be the first to set foot upon Mars. That person — perhaps a child today — will also be standing on the shoulders of countless scientists, engineers, and analogue astronauts who have made and rectified all manner of mistakes to ensure their success. @robotgrrl @alinespacebiker @audrey_drm_ad_astra #MDRS #themarssociety  #analogueastronaut #Mars 
#MarsIsForEveryone #stem #deeptime

For first colonists on Mars, making a home will be an arduous process spread across generations. Not only will they live in a place with no existing culture, but they will also live in an environment completely inhospitable to human life, with no breathable air or running water. This Sol I was up at dawn and projected videos of water and forest on the walls of the Science Dome at @mdrs_utah with the barren landscape outside, imagining ways Martian habitats can bring for a sense of earth. Distance isn't merely a spatial concept. If we think of time as a flowing river, then each moment is an island in that river, each separated from the others by the relentless current of time. Consider standing at Mars Desert Research Station, your feet grounded in the same soil, separated not by miles but by millennia. Some 145 million years ago to 150 million years ago, dinosaurs roamed this landscape, the remnants of their existence still being unearthed by paleontologists working at the nearby Hanksville-Burpee Dinosaur Quarry. The same latitude and longitude, yet a chasm of a million years stretches between them. The temporal distance between these moments is profound and poignant, a vivid demonstration of how time itself is a kind of distance, no less real than the vast expanse between Earth and Mars #deeptime #STEM #Mars #MDRS #themarssociety #analogueastronaut

This is my friend, artist Autumn Lyn @autumn.lyn.ny in front of a small section of her 50-meter-long artwork about the profound losses of Covid. Every time I am near this piece I get goosebumps. 

Name: "Om Mani's Symphony: A Tribute to 6,881,955+ Souls" 
Material: Oil stamp ink on canvas
Size: 2.1x 50 meters
Year: 2020-2023

In Autumn’s own words: “After my grandma succumbed to Covid-19 in April 2020, I felt compelled to embark on this personal project: documenting the staggering number of lives lost worldwide due to the pandemic by memorializing each individual's passing by incorporating my fingerprint alongside recitations of the Tibetan Buddhist mantra of compassion, "Om Mani Padme Hum." It will be set ablaze on a mountaintop when the piece completes. I hold onto hope, believing these souls may discover their path toward eternal peace.” 

#covid #pandemic #art #artwork #largescale #saic #saiclowresmfa

A few years ago, I began searching for the Rougarou, the Louisiana were-creature imported from France. It’s been a nonlinear journey through dreamscapes, swamps and brackish waterscapes, backstreet alleys, seeking out all manner of tall tales and half-truths — all without clear beginnings or endings, or citable sources. Myths overtook fragile facts long ago.
 
The Rougarou myth originated in eighteenth-century France, during a time when many people coexisted with wolves in rural environments. France has a significant link to werewolf mythology. This relationship is closely tied to the country's historical interactions with wolves and the widespread fear of rabies, a disease that haunted humanity for millennia until Louis Pasteur developed a vaccine in 1885. Rabies, a virus that can provoke aggressive behavior, altered consciousness, and in its later stages, hallucinations, and paralysis, has striking behavioral changes in both humans and animals. During this period, wolf attacks on humans were alarmingly frequent, which contributed to the spread of werewolf myths.
 
For thousands of years, the only (ineffective) treatment after a bite from a rabid animal was faith-based or magical. In the spirit of ‘simila similibus curantur’ one such treatment was to place a hair of the dog that bit you upon the wound. Southerners still refer to the morning-after-a-wild-night-out cocktail as The Hair of the Dog. #loupgarou #rougarou #louisiana #cajun #hairofthedog

It became abundantly clear at @mdrs_utah last May that maintenance — the ability to repair and MacGyver all kinds of equipment — is a crucial skill for future deep space astronauts. Last week I spent some time watching Peter Dekluyver work on his self-designed, fully functional spacesuit, built entirely out of readily available materials, many sourced from Goodwill. The ring-lock on his helmet? That’s from a pressure cooker!
 
When I first began learning about all this, I was unaware that spacesuits have a liquid under suit that modulates the astronaut’s body temperature in the extreme temperature variations in space. It seems that spacesuits are a most critical component of deep space success, but also, one of the weakest links for so much can go wrong. Peter speaks a language of machines with astounding fluency, and sees ways to re-purpose bits and pieces of various machines to build something new. Watching him work has been one of the more impressive things I have witnessed. I asked him: “Have you ever encountered a machine you didn’t understand?” and he answered, “Analog? No, never.” #futurist #spacesuit
With my “Desert Discoball Timescape” piece installed in my friend @hugh_lau ‘s art filled home 🪩🪩🪩

There is an essay that I have been trying to write for years now, but I can’t even give shape to the topic yet. It is a swirl of these things: seeing my father bloodied up to his elbows in a dying man’s body, the understanding that horror so often exists within an instant the facile, blinding wonder of youth. And, my choice (which I still question) to tell happier stories over harder ones for many years. Will try again tomorrow 💛
